# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: game-loop-timing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:game-loop-timing/control-loop] A **control loop** is the fundamental building block of control systems in general and industrial control systems in particular.
[src:game-loop-timing/control-loop] It consists of the process sensor, the controller function, and the final control element (FCE) which controls the process necessary to automatically adjust the value of a measured process variable (PV) to equal the value of a desired set-point (SP).
[src:game-loop-timing/control-loop] There are two common classes of control loop: open loop and closed loop.
[src:game-loop-timing/control-loop] Fundamentally, there are two types of control loop: *open-loop control* (feedforward), and *closed-loop control* (feedback).
[src:game-loop-timing/control-loop] An example of a control system is a car's cruise control, which is a device designed to maintain vehicle speed at a constant *desired* or *reference* speed provided by the driver.
[src:game-loop-timing/control-loop] The *controller* is the cruise control, the *plant* is the car, and the *system* is the car and the cruise control.
[src:game-loop-timing/control-loop] The system output is the car's speed, and the control itself is the engine's throttle position which determines how much power the engine delivers.
[src:game-loop-timing/control-loop] A primitive way to implement cruise control is simply to lock the throttle position when the driver engages cruise control.
[src:game-loop-timing/control-loop] However, if the cruise control is engaged on a stretch of non-flat road, then the car will travel slower going uphill and faster when going downhill.
[src:game-loop-timing/control-loop] In a *closed-loop control system*, data from a sensor monitoring the car's speed (the system output) enters a controller which continuously compares the quantity representing the speed with the reference quantity representing the desired speed.
[src:game-loop-timing/control-loop] The difference, called the error, determines the throttle position (the control).
[src:game-loop-timing/control-loop] The result is to match the car's speed to the reference speed (maintain the desired system output).
[src:game-loop-timing/control-loop] Now, when the car goes uphill, the difference between the input (the sensed speed) and the reference continuously determines the throttle position.
[src:game-loop-timing/control-loop] As the sensed speed drops below the reference, the difference increases, the throttle opens, and engine power increases, speeding up the vehicle.
[src:game-loop-timing/control-loop] In this way, the controller dynamically counteracts changes to the car's speed.
[src:game-loop-timing/control-loop] The central idea of these control systems is the *feedback loop*, the controller affects the system output, which in turn is measured and fed back to the controller.
[src:game-loop-timing/control-loop] The accompanying diagram shows a control loop with a single PV input, a control function, and the control output (CO) which modulates the action of the final control element (FCE) to alter the value of the manipulated variable (MV).
[src:game-loop-timing/control-loop] In this example, a flow control loop is shown, but can be level, temperature, or any one of many process parameters which need to be controlled.
[src:game-loop-timing/control-loop] The control function shown is an "intermediate type" such as a PID controller which means it can generate a full range of output signals anywhere between 0-100%, rather than just an on/off signal.
[src:game-loop-timing/control-loop] In this example, the value of the PV is always the same as the MV, as they are in series in the pipeline.
[src:game-loop-timing/control-loop] However, if the feed from the valve was to a tank, and the controller function was to control the level using the fill valve, the PV would be the tank level, and the MV would be the flow to the tank.
[src:game-loop-timing/control-loop] The controller function can be a discrete controller or a function block in a computerised control system such as a distributed control system or a programmable logic controller.
[src:game-loop-timing/control-loop] In all cases, a control loop diagram is a very convenient and useful way of representing the control function and its interaction with plant.
[src:game-loop-timing/control-loop] In practice at a process control level, control loops are normally abbreviated using standard symbols in a Piping and instrumentation diagram, which shows all elements of the process measurement and control based on a process flow diagram.
[src:game-loop-timing/control-loop] At a detailed level, the control loop connection diagram is created to show the electrical and pneumatic connections.
[src:game-loop-timing/control-loop] This greatly aids diagnostics and repair, as all the connections for a single control function are on one diagram.
[src:game-loop-timing/control-loop] To aid unique identification of equipment, each loop and its elements are identified by a "tagging" system and each element has a unique tag identification.
[src:game-loop-timing/control-loop] Based on the standards ANSI/ISA S5.1 and ISO 14617-6, the identifications consist of up to 5 letters.
[src:game-loop-timing/control-loop] The first identification letter is for the measured value, the second is a modifier, 3rd indicates the passive/readout function, 4th - active/output function, and the 5th is the function modifier.
[src:game-loop-timing/control-loop] This is followed by loop number, which is unique to that loop.
[src:game-loop-timing/control-loop] For instance, FIC045 means it is the Flow Indicating Controller in control loop 045.
[src:game-loop-timing/control-loop] This is also known as the "tag" identifier of the field device, which is normally given to the location and function of the instrument.
[src:game-loop-timing/control-loop] The same loop may have FT045 - which is the flow transmitter in the same loop.
[src:game-loop-timing/delta-timing] In network programming, due to the unpredictable nature of internet connections, delta timing is used in a similar way to variably update the movement information received via the computer network, regardless of how long it took to receive the next data packet of movement information.
[src:game-loop-timing/delta-timing] It is often done by calling a timer every frame per second that holds the time between now and last call.
[src:game-loop-timing/delta-timing] Thereafter the resulting number (delta time) is used to calculate how far, for instance, a video game character would have travelled during that time.
[src:game-loop-timing/delta-timing] This results in the character taking the same amount of real world time to move across the screen regardless of the rate of update, and whether the delay is caused by lack of processing power or a slow internet connection.
[src:game-loop-timing/delta-timing] In network programming, this keeps the game world of each computer in sync with the others, by making sure each client eventually sees the same activity at the same time, even if more time has passed since the last update for some clients than others.
[src:game-loop-timing/delta-timing] Big enough delays will eventually negatively affect the gameplay experience, but using Delta Time keeps the gameplay consistent so long as the computer and internet connection meet the minimum hardware requirements of the game.
[src:game-loop-timing/delta-timing] Delta time can be used to measure how long a given program took to execute in real-time.
[src:game-loop-timing/delta-timing] The python snippet below shows how an example function's execution time can be calculated using the delta of times before and after execution.
[src:game-loop-timing/delta-timing] Delta-time and frame rate are not always related.
[src:game-loop-timing/delta-timing] Video games fall into one of two categories regarding frame rate: frame rate dependent or frame rate independent.
[src:game-loop-timing/delta-timing] Frame rate Dependent games have a frame rate that varies based on the computer running the software.
[src:game-loop-timing/delta-timing] For example, if a frame rate dependent game runs at 300 frames per second (fps) on a computer with a refresh rate of 120 hertz (Hz), then it would run at 150 fps on a computer with a refresh rate of 60 Hz.
[src:game-loop-timing/delta-timing] A standard delta-time expression can create pause screens and intentional slow-motion effects in frame rate-dependent games.
[src:game-loop-timing/delta-timing] Standard delta-time formulas are seldom used for standard game-play because the delta-time between frames varies greatly depending on the refresh rate of the computer on which it is running.
[src:game-loop-timing/delta-timing] If a game is frame rate independent, the frame rate is preset and runs identically across all computers regardless of their specifications.
[src:game-loop-timing/delta-timing] Frame rate independence limits the maximum graphics quality to make the game available to more consumers.
[src:game-loop-timing/delta-timing] Frame rate independence is particularly popular in mobile games and games optimized for lower-end computers such as Chromebooks.
[src:game-loop-timing/delta-timing] In frame rate independent games, the delta-time between frames is consistent across the entire game.
[src:game-loop-timing/delta-timing] This standardization means that one delta-time expression can create a consistent frame rate for all users on all types of computers.
[src:game-loop-timing/delta-timing] Delta-timing can excel anytime a game's frame rate needs to be independent of its hardware.
[src:game-loop-timing/delta-timing] One example of this could be games that need to run on mobile devices or low-end computers.
[src:game-loop-timing/delta-timing] In some cases, video game developers use delta-timing to standardize the movement speed of an object on the screen.
[src:game-loop-timing/delta-timing] For example, if a character moves across the screen at a constant rate, delta-timing can ensure that this movement speed is consistent and does not fluctuate.
[src:game-loop-timing/delta-timing] Using delta-timing for movement is particularly useful for users who possess inconsistent internet or low-end computer hardware.
[src:game-loop-timing/delta-timing] This method can also regulate the movement of on-screen objects.
[src:game-loop-timing/delta-timing] One disadvantage of using delta-timing for movement is that it can be complicated for games that incorporate a wide variety of movements and movement speeds.
[src:game-loop-timing/delta-timing] For example, a game could have a specified walking speed and sprinting speed for all characters; however, characters may also drive cars, boats, planes, and other vehicles.
[src:game-loop-timing/delta-timing] If the developer wants each of these movement speeds to be different (to make the game as realistic as possible), they would need a separate delta-time expression for each movement speed (that is only assuming these movements occur at a constant rate).
[src:game-loop-timing/delta-timing] If the movements do not occur at a constant rate, delta-timing expressions are rendered ineffective.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] The temporal sensitivity and resolution of human vision vary depending on the type and characteristics of the visual stimulus, and it differs between individuals.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] The human visual system can process 10 to 12 images per second and perceive them individually, while higher rates are perceived as motion.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] Modulated light (such as a computer display) is perceived as stable by the majority of participants in studies when the rate is higher than 50 FPS.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] This perception of modulated light as steady is known as the flicker fusion threshold.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] However, when the modulated light is non-uniform and contains an image, the flicker fusion threshold can be much higher, in the hundreds of hertz.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] With regard to image recognition, people have been found to recognize a specific image in an unbroken series of different images, each of which lasts as little as 13 milliseconds.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] Persistence of vision sometimes accounts for very short single-millisecond visual stimulus having a perceived duration of between 100 ms and 400 ms.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] Multiple stimuli that are very short are sometimes perceived as a single stimulus, such as a 10 ms green flash of light immediately followed by a 10 ms red flash of light perceived as a single yellow flash of light.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] Early silent films had stated frame rates anywhere from 16 to 24 frames per second (FPS), but since the cameras were hand-cranked, the rate often changed during the scene to fit the mood.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] Projectionists could also change the frame rate in the theater by adjusting a rheostat controlling the voltage powering the film-carrying mechanism in the projector.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] Film companies often intended for theaters to show their silent films at a higher frame rate than that at which they were filmed.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] These frame rates were enough for the sense of motion, but it was perceived as jerky motion.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] To minimize the perceived flicker, projectors employed dual- and triple-blade shutters, so each frame was displayed two or three times, increasing the flicker rate to 48 or 72 FPS and reducing eye strain.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] Thomas Edison said that 46 frames per second was the minimum needed for the eye to perceive motion: "Anything less will strain the eye." In the mid to late 1920s, the frame rate for silent film increased to 20–26 FPS.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] When sound film was introduced in 1926, variations in film speed were no longer tolerated, as the human ear is more sensitive than the eye to changes in frequency.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] Many theaters had shown silent films at 22 to 26 FPS, which is why the industry chose 24 FPS for sound film as a compromise.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] From 1927 to 1930, as various studios updated equipment, the rate of 24 FPS became standard for 35 mm sound film.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] At 24 FPS, the film travels through the projector at a rate of 456 millimetres (18.0 in) per second.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] This allowed simple two-blade shutters to give a projected series of images at 48 per second, satisfying Edison's recommendation.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] Many modern 35 mm film projectors use three-blade shutters to give 72 images per second—each frame is flashed on screen three times.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] In drawn animation, moving characters are often animated *on twos*, meaning one drawing is displayed for every two frames of film.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] Since film typically runs at 24 frames per second, this results in a display of only 12 drawings per second.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] Even though the image update rate is low, the fluidity is satisfactory for most subjects.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] However, when a character is required to perform a quick movement, it is usually necessary to revert to animating *on ones*, as *twos* are too slow to convey the motion adequately.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] A blend of the two techniques keeps the eye fooled and controls production cost.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] Animation for most Saturday morning cartoons, first introduced in the mid-1960s, was produced as cheaply as possible and was most often shot on *threes* or even *fours*, i.e., three or four frames per drawing.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] This translates to only 8 or 6 drawings per second, respectively.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] Anime is also usually drawn on threes or twos.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] Due to the mains frequency of electric grids, analog television broadcast was developed with frame rates of 50 FPS (most of the world) or 60 FPS (Canada, US, Mexico, Philippines, Japan, South Korea).
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] The frequency of the electricity grid was extremely stable and therefore it was logical to use for synchronization.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] The introduction of color television technology made it necessary to lower that 60 FPS frequency by 0.1% to avoid "dot crawl", a display artifact appearing on legacy black-and-white displays, showing up on highly color-saturated surfaces.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] It was found that by lowering the frame rate by 0.1%, the undesirable effect was minimized.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] As of 2025, video transmission standards in North America, Japan, and South Korea are still based on 60/1.001 ≈ 59.94 images per second.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] Confusingly, *interlaced* formats are customarily stated at half their image rate, 29.97/25 FPS, and *double* their image height, but these statements are purely custom; in each format, 60 images per second are produced.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] A resolution of 1080i produces 59.94 or 50 1920 × 540 images, each squashed to half-height in the photographic process and stretched back to fill the screen on playback in a television set.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] The 720p format produces 59.94/50 or 29.97/25 1280 × 720 images, not squeezed, so that no expansion or squeezing of the image is necessary.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] This confusion was industry-wide in the early days of digital video software, with much software being written incorrectly, the developers believing that only 29.97 images were expected each second.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] While it was true that each picture element was polled and sent only 29.97 times per second, the pixel location immediately below that one was polled 1/60 of a second later, part of a completely separate image for the next 1/60-second frame.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] At its native 24 FPS rate, film could not be displayed on 60 FPS video without the necessary pulldown process, often leading to *judder*: to convert 24 frames per second into 60 frames per second, every odd frame is repeated, playing twice, while every even frame is tripled.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] This creates uneven motion, appearing stroboscopic.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] Other conversions have similar uneven frame doubling.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] Newer video standards support 120, 240, or 300 frames per second, so frames can be evenly sampled for standard frame rates such as 24, 48 and 60 FPS film or 25, 30, 50 or 60 FPS video.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] Of course these higher frame rates may also be displayed at their native rates.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] In computer video games, frame rate plays an important part in the experience as, unlike film, games are rendered in real-time.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] 60 frames per second has for a long time been considered the minimum frame rate for smoothly animated game play.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] Video games designed for PAL markets, before the sixth generation of video game consoles, had lower frame rates by design due to the 50 Hz output.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] This noticeably made fast-paced games, such as racing or fighting games, run slower; less frequently developers accounted for the frame rate difference and altered the game code to achieve (nearly) identical pacing across both regions, with varying degrees of success.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] Computer monitors marketed to competitive PC gamers can hit 360, 500 FPS, or more.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] High frame rates make action scenes look less blurry, such as sprinting through the wilderness in an open world game, spinning rapidly to face an opponent in a first-person shooter, or keeping track of details during an intense fight in a multiplayer online battle arena.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] Some people may have difficulty perceiving the differences between high frame rates, though.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] Frame time is related to frame rate, but it measures the time between frames.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] A game could maintain an average of 60 frames per second but appear choppy because of a poor frame time.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] Game reviews sometimes average the worst 1% of frame rates, reported as the 99th percentile, to measure how choppy the game appears.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] A small difference between the average frame rate and 99th percentile would generally indicate a smooth experience.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] To mitigate the choppiness of poorly optimized games, players can set frame rate caps closer to their 99% percentile.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] When a game's frame rate is different from the display's refresh rate, screen tearing can occur.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] Vsync mitigates this, but it caps the frame rate to the display's refresh rate, increases input lag, and introduces judder.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] Variable refresh rate displays automatically set their refresh rate equal to the game's frame rate, as long as it is within the display's supported range.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] Frame rate up-conversion (FRC) is the process of increasing the temporal resolution of a video sequence by synthesizing one or more intermediate frames between two consecutive frames.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] A low frame rate causes aliasing, yields abrupt motion artifacts, and degrades the video quality.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] Consequently, the temporal resolution is an important factor affecting video quality.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] Algorithms for FRC are widely used in applications, including visual quality enhancement, video compression and slow-motion video generation.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] Most FRC methods can be categorized into optical flow or kernel-based and pixel hallucination-based methods.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] Flow-based methods linearly combine predicted optical flows between two input frames to approximate flows from the target intermediate frame to the input frames.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] They also propose flow reversal (projection) for more accurate image warping.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] Moreover, there are algorithms that give different weights of overlapped flow vectors depending on the object depth of the scene via a flow projection layer.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] Pixel hallucination-based methods use deformable convolution to the center frame generator by replacing optical flows with offset vectors.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] There are algorithms that also interpolate middle frames with the help of deformable convolution in the feature domain.
[src:game-loop-timing/frame-rate] However, since these methods directly hallucinate pixels, unlike the flow-based FRC methods, the predicted frames tend to be blurry when fast-moving objects are present.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] In analysis, **numerical integration** comprises a broad family of algorithms for calculating the numerical value of a definite integral.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] The term **numerical quadrature** (often abbreviated to **quadrature**) is more or less a synonym for "numerical integration", especially as applied to one-dimensional integrals.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] Some authors refer to numerical integration over more than one dimension as **cubature**; others take "quadrature" to include higher-dimensional integration.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] If *f*(*x*) is a smooth function integrated over a small number of dimensions, and the domain of integration is bounded, there are many methods for approximating the integral to the desired precision.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] Numerical integration has roots in the geometrical problem of finding a square with the same area as a given plane figure (*quadrature* or *squaring*), as in the quadrature of the circle.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] The term is also sometimes used to describe the numerical solution of differential equations.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] A formula for the integrand may be known, but it may be difficult or impossible to find an antiderivative that is an elementary function.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] An example of such an integrand is *f* (*x*) = exp(−*x*2), the antiderivative of which (the error function, times a constant) cannot be written in elementary form .
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] It may be possible to find an antiderivative symbolically, but it may be easier to compute a numerical approximation than to compute the antiderivative.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] That may be the case if the antiderivative is given as an infinite series or product, or if its evaluation requires a special function that is not available.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] The term "numerical integration" first appears in 1915 in the publication *A Course in Interpolation and Numeric Integration for the Mathematical Laboratory* by David Gibb.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] "Quadrature" is a historical mathematical term that means calculating area.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] Quadrature problems have served as one of the main sources of mathematical analysis.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] Mathematicians of Ancient Greece, according to the Pythagorean doctrine, understood calculation of area as the process of constructing geometrically a square having the same area (*squaring*) — that is why the process was named "quadrature".
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] Examples include quadrature of the circle, Lune of Hippocrates, and the treatise *Quadrature of the Parabola*.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] This construction must be performed only by means of compass and straightedge.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] The ancient Babylonians used the trapezoidal rule to integrate the motion of Jupiter along the ecliptic.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] For a quadrature of a rectangle with the sides *a* and *b* it is necessary to construct a square with the side $x={\sqrt {ab}}$ (the geometric mean of *a* and *b*).
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] For this purpose it is possible to use the following fact: if we draw the circle with the sum of *a* and *b* as the diameter, then the height BH (from a point of their connection to crossing with a circle) equals their geometric mean.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] The similar geometrical construction solves a problem of a quadrature for a parallelogram and a triangle.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] Problems of quadrature for curvilinear figures are much more difficult.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] The quadrature of the circle with compass and straightedge had been proved in the 19th century to be impossible.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] Nevertheless, for some figures (for example the lune of Hippocrates) a quadrature can be performed.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] The quadratures of a sphere surface and a parabola segment done by Archimedes became the highest achievement of the antique analysis.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] To prove the results, Archimedes used the method of exhaustion of Eudoxus.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] In medieval Europe the quadrature meant calculation of area by any method.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] More often the method of indivisibles was used; it was less rigorous, but more simple and powerful.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] John Wallis algebrised this method: he wrote in his *Arithmetica Infinitorum* (1656) series that we now call the definite integral, and he calculated their values.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] Isaac Barrow and James Gregory made further progress: quadratures for some algebraic curves and spirals.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] Christiaan Huygens successfully performed a quadrature of some solids of revolution.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] The quadrature of the hyperbola by Saint-Vincent and de Sarasa provided a new function, the natural logarithm, of critical importance.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] With the invention of integral calculus came a universal method for area calculation.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] In response, the term "quadrature" has become traditional, and instead the modern phrase "*computation of a univariate definite integral*" is more common.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] A **quadrature rule** is an approximation of the definite integral of a function, usually stated as a weighted sum of function values at specified points within the domain of integration.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] Numerical integration methods can generally be described as combining evaluations of the integrand to get an approximation to the integral.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] The integrand is evaluated at a finite set of points called ***integration points*** and a weighted sum of these values is used to approximate the integral.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] The integration points and weights depend on the specific method used and the accuracy required from the approximation.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] An important part of the analysis of any numerical integration method is to study the behavior of the approximation error as a function of the number of integrand evaluations.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] A method that yields a small error for a small number of evaluations is usually considered superior.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] Reducing the number of evaluations of the integrand reduces the number of arithmetic operations involved, and therefore reduces the total error.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] Also, each evaluation takes time, and the integrand may be arbitrarily complicated.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] A "brute force" kind of numerical integration can be done, if the integrand is reasonably well-behaved (i.e. piecewise continuous and of bounded variation), by evaluating the integrand with very small increments.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] This simplest method approximates the function by a step function (a piecewise constant function, or a segmented polynomial of degree zero) that passes through the point ${\textstyle \left({\frac {a+b}{2}},f\left({\frac {a+b}{2}}\right)\right)}$ .
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] A large class of quadrature rules can be derived by constructing interpolating functions that are easy to integrate.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] Typically these interpolating functions are polynomials.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] In practice, since polynomials of very high degree tend to oscillate wildly, only polynomials of low degree are used, typically linear and quadratic.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] The interpolating function may be a straight line (an affine function, i.e. a polynomial of degree 1) passing through the points $\left(a,f(a)\right)$ and $\left(b,f(b)\right)$ .
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] For either one of these rules, we can make a more accurate approximation by breaking up the interval $[a,b]$ into some number n of subintervals, computing an approximation for each subinterval, then adding up all the results.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] This is called a *composite rule*, *extended rule*, or *iterated rule*.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] where the subintervals have the form $[a+kh,a+(k+1)h]\subset [a,b],$ with ${\textstyle h={\frac {b-a}{n}}}$ and $k=0,\ldots ,n-1.$ Here we used subintervals of the same length h but one could also use intervals of varying length $\left(h_{k}\right)_{k}$ .
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] Interpolation with polynomials evaluated at equally spaced points in $[a,b]$ yields the Newton–Cotes formulas, of which the rectangle rule and the trapezoidal rule are examples.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] Simpson's rule, which is based on a polynomial of order 2, is also a Newton–Cotes formula.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] Quadrature rules with equally spaced points have the very convenient property of *nesting*.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] The corresponding rule with each interval subdivided includes all the current points, so those integrand values can be re-used.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] If we allow the intervals between interpolation points to vary, we find another group of quadrature formulas, such as the Gaussian quadrature formulas.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] A Gaussian quadrature rule is typically more accurate than a Newton–Cotes rule that uses the same number of function evaluations, if the integrand is smooth (i.e., if it is sufficiently differentiable).
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] Other quadrature methods with varying intervals include Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature (also called Fejér quadrature) methods, which do nest.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] Gaussian quadrature rules do not nest, but the related Gauss–Kronrod quadrature formulas do.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] Adaptive quadrature is a numerical integration method in which the integral of a function $f(x)$ is approximated using static quadrature rules on adaptively refined subintervals of the region of integration.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] Generally, adaptive algorithms are just as efficient and effective as traditional algorithms for "well behaved" integrands, but are also effective for "badly behaved" integrands for which traditional algorithms may fail.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] The accuracy of a quadrature rule of the Newton–Cotes type is generally a function of the number of evaluation points.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] The result is usually more accurate as the number of evaluation points increases, or, equivalently, as the width of the step size between the points decreases.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] It is natural to ask what the result would be if the step size were allowed to approach zero.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] This can be answered by extrapolating the result from two or more nonzero step sizes, using series acceleration methods such as Richardson extrapolation.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] The extrapolation function may be a polynomial or rational function.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] Extrapolation methods are described in more detail by Stoer and Bulirsch (Section 3.4) and are implemented in many of the routines in the QUADPACK library.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] where the supremum was used to approximate.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] Hence, if we approximate the integral ${\textstyle \int _{a}^{b}f(x)\,dx}$ by the quadrature rule $(b-a)f(a)$ our error is no greater than the right hand side of **1**.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] We can convert this into an error analysis for the Riemann sum, giving an upper bound of ${\frac {n^{-1}}{2}}\sup _{0\leq x\leq 1}\left|f'(x)\right|$ for the error term of that particular approximation.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] (Note that this is precisely the error we calculated for the example $f(x)=x$ .) Using more derivatives, and by tweaking the quadrature, we can do a similar error analysis using a Taylor series (using a partial sum with remainder term) for *f*.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] This error analysis gives a strict upper bound on the error, if the derivatives of *f* are available.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] This integration method can be combined with interval arithmetic to produce computer proofs and *verified* calculations.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] Several methods exist for approximate integration over unbounded intervals.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] The standard technique involves specially derived quadrature rules, such as Gauss-Hermite quadrature for integrals on the whole real line and Gauss-Laguerre quadrature for integrals on the positive reals.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] The quadrature rules discussed so far are all designed to compute one-dimensional integrals.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] To compute integrals in multiple dimensions, one approach is to phrase the multiple integral as repeated one-dimensional integrals by applying Fubini's theorem (the tensor product rule).
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] This approach requires the function evaluations to grow exponentially as the number of dimensions increases.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] Three methods are known to overcome this so-called *curse of dimensionality*.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] A great many additional techniques for forming multidimensional cubature integration rules for a variety of weighting functions are given in the monograph by Stroud.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] Integration on the sphere has been reviewed by Hesse et al.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] Monte Carlo methods and quasi-Monte Carlo methods are easy to apply to multi-dimensional integrals.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] They may yield greater accuracy for the same number of function evaluations than repeated integrations using one-dimensional methods.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] A large class of useful Monte Carlo methods are the so-called Markov chain Monte Carlo algorithms, which include the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm and Gibbs sampling.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] Sparse grids were originally developed by Smolyak for the quadrature of high-dimensional functions.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] The method is always based on a one-dimensional quadrature rule, but performs a more sophisticated combination of univariate results.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] However, whereas the tensor product rule guarantees that the weights of all of the cubature points will be positive if the weights of the quadrature points were positive, Smolyak's rule does not guarantee that the weights will all be positive.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] Bayesian quadrature is a statistical approach to the numerical problem of computing integrals and falls under the field of probabilistic numerics.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] It can provide a full handling of the uncertainty over the solution of the integral expressed as a Gaussian process posterior variance.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] can be reduced to an initial value problem for an ordinary differential equation by applying the first part of the fundamental theorem of calculus.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] Numerical methods for ordinary differential equations, such as Runge–Kutta methods, can be applied to the restated problem and thus be used to evaluate the integral.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] For instance, the standard fourth-order Runge–Kutta method applied to the differential equation yields Simpson's rule from above.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] The differential equation $F'(x)=f(x)$ has a special form: the right-hand side contains only the independent variable (here x ) and not the dependent variable (here F ).
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] This simplifies the theory and algorithms considerably.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] The problem of evaluating integrals is thus best studied in its own right.
[src:game-loop-timing/numerical-integration] Conversely, the term "quadrature" may also be used for the solution of differential equations: "solving by quadrature" or "reduction to quadrature" means expressing its solution in terms of integrals.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is also used in simulation to mean that the simulation's clock runs at the same speed as a real clock.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] Real-time responses are often understood to be in the order of milliseconds, and sometimes microseconds.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] A system not specified as operating in real time cannot usually *guarantee* a response within any timeframe, although *typical* or *expected* response times may be given.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] Real-time processing *fails* if not completed within a specified deadline relative to an event; deadlines must always be met, regardless of system load.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] A real-time system has been described as one which "controls an environment by receiving data, processing them, and returning the results sufficiently quickly to affect the environment at that time".
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is used in process control and enterprise systems to mean "without significant delay".
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] Real-time software may use one or more of the following: synchronous programming languages, real-time operating systems (RTOSes), and real-time networks.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] Each of these provides essential frameworks on which to build a real-time software application.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] Systems used for many safety-critical applications must be real-time, such as for control of fly-by-wire aircraft, or anti-lock brakes, both of which demand immediate and accurate mechanical response.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] The term *real-time* derives from its use in early simulation, where a real-world process is simulated at a rate which matched that of the real process (now called real-time simulation to avoid ambiguity).
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] Analog computers, most often, were capable of simulating at a much faster pace than real-time, a situation that could be just as dangerous as a slow simulation if it were not also recognized and accounted for.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] Minicomputers, particularly from the 1970s onwards, when built into dedicated embedded systems such as DOG (digital on-screen graphic) scanners, increased the need for low-latency priority-driven responses to important interactions with incoming data.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] Operating systems such as Data General's RDOS (Real-Time Disk Operating System) and RTOS with background and foreground scheduling as well as Digital Equipment Corporation's RT-11 date from this era.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] Background-foreground scheduling allowed low-priority tasks CPU time when no foreground task needed to execute, and gave absolute priority within the foreground to threads/tasks with the highest priority.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] Real-time operating systems would also be used for time-sharing multiuser duties.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] For example, Data General Business Basic could run in the foreground or background of RDOS and would introduce additional elements to the scheduling algorithm to make it more appropriate for people interacting via dumb terminals.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] Early personal computers were sometimes used for real-time computing.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] The possibility of deactivating other interrupts allowed for hard-coded loops with defined timing, and the low interrupt latency allowed the implementation of a real-time operating system, giving the user interface and the disk drives lower priority than the real-time thread.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] However, several coding libraries exist that offer real-time capabilities in a high-level language on a variety of operating systems, for example, Real-time Java.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] Later microprocessors such as the Motorola 68000 and subsequent family members (68010, 68020, ColdFire, etc.) also became popular with manufacturers of industrial control systems.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] This application area is one where real-time control offers genuine advantages in terms of process performance and safety.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] A system is said to be *real-time* if the total correctness of an operation depends not only upon its logical correctness, but also upon the time in which it is performed.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] Thus, the goal of a *hard real-time system* is to ensure that all deadlines are met, but for *soft real-time systems* the goal becomes meeting a certain subset of deadlines in order to optimize some application-specific criteria.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] The particular criteria optimized depend on the application, but some typical examples include maximizing the number of deadlines met, minimizing the lateness of tasks and maximizing the number of high-priority tasks meeting their deadlines.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] In the context of multitasking systems the scheduling policy is normally priority driven (pre-emptive schedulers).
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] In some situations, these can guarantee hard real-time performance (for instance, if the set of tasks and their priorities is known in advance).
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] There are other hard real-time schedulers such as rate-monotonic, which is not common in general-purpose systems, as it requires additional information in order to schedule a task: namely, a bound or worst-case estimate for how long the task must execute.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] Specific algorithms for scheduling such hard real-time tasks exist, like earliest deadline first, which, ignoring the overhead of context switching, is sufficient for system loads of less than 100%.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] New overlay scheduling systems, such as an adaptive partition scheduler assist in managing large systems with a mixture of hard real-time and non real-time applications.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] In a real-time digital signal processing (DSP) process, the analyzed (input) and generated (output) samples can be processed (or generated) continuously in the time it takes to input and output the same set of samples *independent* of the processing delay.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] It means that the processing delay must be bounded even if the processing continues for an unlimited time.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] The mean processing time per sample, including overhead, is no greater than the sampling period, which is the reciprocal of the sampling rate.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] This is the criterion whether the samples are grouped together in large segments and processed as blocks or are processed individually and whether there are long, short, or non-existent input and output buffers.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] Consider an audio DSP example; if a process requires 2.01 seconds to analyze, synthesize, or process 2.00 seconds of sound, it is not real-time.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] However, if it takes 1.99 seconds, it is or can be made into a real-time DSP process.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] A common life analogy is standing in a line or queue waiting for the checkout in a grocery store.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] If the line asymptotically grows longer and longer without bound, the checkout process is not real-time.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] If the length of the line is bounded, customers are being "processed" and output as rapidly, on average, as they are being inputted, then that process *is* real-time.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] The grocer might go out of business or must at least lose business if they cannot make their checkout process real-time; thus, it is fundamentally important that this process is real-time.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] A signal processing algorithm that cannot keep up with the flow of input data, with output falling further and further behind the input, is not real-time.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] If the delay of the output (relative to the input) is bounded regarding a process that operates over an unlimited time, then that signal processing algorithm is real-time, even if the throughput delay may be very long.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] Real-time signal processing is necessary, but not sufficient in and of itself, for live signal processing such as what is required in live event support.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] Live audio digital signal processing requires both real-time operation and a sufficient limit to throughput delay so as to be tolerable to performers using stage monitors or in-ear monitors and not noticeable as lip sync error by the audience also directly watching the performers.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] Tolerable limits to latency for live, real-time processing is a subject of investigation and debate, but is estimated to be between 6 and 20 milliseconds.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] Real-time bidirectional telecommunications delays of less than 300 ms ("round trip" or twice the unidirectional delay) are considered "acceptable" to avoid undesired "talk-over" in conversation.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] Real-time computing is sometimes misunderstood to be high-performance computing, but this is not an accurate classification.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] For example, a massive supercomputer executing a scientific simulation may offer impressive performance, yet it is not executing a real-time computation.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] Conversely, once the hardware and software for an anti-lock braking system have been designed to meet its required deadlines, no further performance gains are obligatory or even useful.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] Furthermore, if a network server is highly loaded with network traffic, its response time may be slower, but will (in most cases) still succeed before it times out (hits its deadline).
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] Hence, such a network server would not be considered a real-time system: temporal failures (delays, time-outs, etc.) are typically small and compartmentalized (limited in effect), but are not catastrophic failures.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] In a real-time system, such as the FTSE 100 Index, a slowdown beyond limits would often be considered catastrophic in its application context.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] The most important requirement of a real-time system is consistent output, not high throughput.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] Some kinds of software, such as many chess-playing programs, can fall into either category.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] For instance, a chess program designed to play in a tournament with a clock will need to decide on a move before a certain deadline or lose the game, and is therefore a real-time computation, but a chess program that is allowed to run indefinitely before moving is not.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] In both of these cases, however, high performance is desirable: the more work a tournament chess program can do in the allotted time, the better its moves will be, and the faster an unconstrained chess program runs, the sooner it will be able to move.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] High performance is indicative of the amount of processing that is performed in a given amount of time, whereas real-time is the ability to get done with the processing to yield a useful output in the available time.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] For example, a near-real-time display depicts an event or situation as it existed at the current time minus the processing time, as nearly the time of the live event.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] The distinction between the terms "near real time" and "real time" is somewhat nebulous and must be defined for the situation at hand.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] The term implies that there are no significant delays.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] In many cases, processing described as "real-time" would be more accurately described as "near real-time".
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] Near real-time also refers to delayed real-time transmission of voice and video.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] It allows playing video images, in approximately real-time, without having to wait for an entire large video file to download.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] Incompatible databases can export/import to common flat files that the other database can import/export on a scheduled basis so they can sync/share common data in "near real-time" with each other.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] Several methods exist to aid the design of real-time systems, an example of which is MASCOT, an old but very successful method that represents the concurrent structure of the system.
[src:game-loop-timing/real-time-computing] Other examples are HOOD, Real-Time UML, AADL, the Ravenscar profile, and Real-time Java.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] In reference to terminology originating with cathode-ray tubes (CRTs), the **refresh rate**, also known as **vertical refresh rate**, **vertical scan rate** or **vertical frequency**, is the number of times per second that a raster-based display device displays a new image.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] This can be independent from frame rate, which describes how many images are stored or generated every second by the device driving the display.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] On CRT displays, higher refresh rates produce less flickering, thereby reducing eye strain.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] In other technologies, such as liquid-crystal displays, the refresh rate affects only how often the image can potentially be updated.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Non-raster displays may not have a characteristic refresh rate.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Vector displays, for instance, do not trace the entire screen, only the actual lines comprising the displayed image, so refresh speed may differ by the size and complexity of the image data.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] For computer programs or telemetry, the term is sometimes applied to how frequently a datum is updated with a new external value from another source (for example; a shared public spreadsheet or hardware feed).
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] While all raster display devices have a characteristic refresh rate, the physical implementation differs between technologies.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Raster-scan CRTs by their nature must refresh the screen since their phosphors will fade and the image will disappear quickly unless refreshed regularly.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] In a CRT, the vertical scan rate is the number of times per second that the electron beam returns to the upper left corner of the screen to begin drawing a new frame.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] It is controlled by the vertical blanking signal generated by the video controller, and is partially limited by the monitor's maximum horizontal scan rate.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] The refresh rate can be calculated from the horizontal scan rate by dividing the scanning frequency by the number of horizontal lines, plus some amount of time to allow for the beam to return to the top.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] By convention, this is a 1.05x multiplier.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] For instance, a monitor with a horizontal scanning frequency of 96 kHz at a resolution of 1280 × 1024 results in a refresh rate of 96,000 ÷ (1024 × 1.05) ≈ 89 Hz (rounded down).
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] CRT refresh rates have historically been an important factor in video game programming.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] In early videogame systems, the only time available for computation was during the vertical blanking interval, during which the beam is returning to the top right corner of the screen and no image is being drawn.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Even in modern games, however, it is important to avoid altering the computer's video buffer except during the vertical retrace, to prevent flickering graphics or screen tearing.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Unlike CRTs, where the image will fade unless refreshed, the pixels of liquid-crystal displays retain their state for as long as power is provided.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Consequently, there is no intrinsic flicker regardless of refresh rate.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Vsync options can eliminate screen tearing by rendering the whole image at the same time.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] On smaller CRT monitors (up to about 15 in or 38 cm), few people notice any discomfort between 60–72 Hz.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] On larger CRT monitors (17 in or 43 cm or larger), most people experience mild discomfort unless the refresh is set to 72 Hz or higher.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] A rate of 100 Hz is comfortable at almost any size.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] However, this does not apply to LCD monitors.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] The closest equivalent to a refresh rate on an LCD monitor is its frame rate, which is often locked at 60 fps.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] But this is rarely a problem, because the only part of an LCD monitor that could produce CRT-like flicker—its backlight—typically operates at around a minimum of 200 Hz.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Different operating systems set the default refresh rate differently.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Microsoft Windows 95 and Windows 98 (First and Second Editions) set the refresh rate to the highest rate that they believe the display supports.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Windows NT-based operating systems and their descendants, including Windows 11, set the default refresh rate to a conservative rate, usually 60 Hz.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Most Linux distributions follow the same behavior, but some are able to dynamically set a default based on the monitor's refresh rate.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Since macOS is normally used exclusively on Apple devices and products, most versions of macOS are locked to 60 Hz with exceptions like later MacBook Pro models.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Some fullscreen applications, including many games, now allow the user to reconfigure the refresh rate before entering fullscreen mode, but most default to a conservative resolution and refresh rate and let you increase the settings in the options.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Old monitors could be damaged if a user set the video card to a refresh rate higher than the highest rate supported by the monitor.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Some models of monitors display a notice that the video signal uses an unsupported refresh rate.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Some displays support variable refresh rate (VRR), the ability to change their refresh rate on-the-fly.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] VRR can be used to save power by allowing the system to spend less performance rendering frames, a technique seen on some mobile devices like smartphones and laptops.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Some computer monitors feature VRR to lower input latency, typically that of a video game, by delay refreshing of the display until a new frame is sent from the graphics card.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] FreeSync and G-Sync are implementations of VRR seen in AMD and Nvidia's graphics card, respectively.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Beginning in the 2010s, competitive video gaming prompted manufacturers to develop displays with higher refresh rates than the standard 60 Hz.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] This responded to the relationship between display latency and player response time in first-person shooter and real-time strategy games.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] The first 144 Hz displays appeared in 2012, with the 24-inch ASUS VG248QE released in 2013.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] At 144 Hz, the monitor reduced frame persistence to approximately 6.9 milliseconds, compared to 16.7 milliseconds at 60 Hz.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] The progression continued through the 2010s.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] In 2017, ASUS released the ROG Swift PG258Q, one of the first 240 Hz monitors, using a twisted nematic (TN) panel at 1920 × 1080 resolution.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] The 240 Hz refresh rate reduced frame persistence to approximately 4.2 milliseconds.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Higher resolutions at 240 Hz proved more demanding for graphics hardware, making full HD the practical standard for this refresh rate category.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] In 2020, ASUS released the ROG Swift PG259QN, the first monitor to achieve 360 Hz, using a "Fast IPS" panel rather than the TN panels previously used for high-refresh displays.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] In 2023, ASUS introduced the ROG Swift Pro PG248QP, which reached 540 Hz through an overclock of its native 360 Hz "Esports TN" panel.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] At 540 Hz, frame persistence drops to approximately 1.85 milliseconds.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Sustaining such refresh rates required a high-end graphics processor; testing showed that at 540 Hz and 1920 × 1080 resolution, a NVIDIA RTX 4090 could be fully utilized depending on game settings and title demands.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] In May 2026, LG Electronics announced the UltraGear 25G590B, marketed as the world's first gaming monitor with a native 1000 Hz refresh rate at full HD (1920 × 1080) resolution, with expected availability in the second half of 2026.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] The 24.5-inch display uses an IPS panel with a backlight-based motion blur reduction system.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Unlike earlier 1000 Hz monitor demonstrations that required switching to 1280 × 720 resolution to reach the refresh rate, the 25G590B maintains 1000 Hz performance at native 1080p.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] When LCD shutter glasses are used for stereo 3D displays, the effective refresh rate is halved, because each eye needs a separate picture.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] For this reason, it is usually recommended to use a display capable of at least 120 Hz, because divided in half this rate is again 60 Hz.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Higher refresh rates result in greater image stability, for example 72 Hz non-stereo is 144 Hz stereo, and 90 Hz non-stereo is 180 Hz stereo.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Most low-end computer graphics cards and monitors cannot handle these high refresh rates, especially at higher resolutions.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] For LCD monitors the pixel brightness changes are much slower than CRT or plasma phosphors.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Typically LCD pixel brightness changes are faster when voltage is applied than when voltage is removed, resulting in an asymmetric pixel response time.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] With 3D shutter glasses this can result in a blurry smearing of the display and poor depth perception, due to the previous image frame not fading to black fast enough as the next frame is drawn.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] The development of televisions in the 1930s was determined by a number of technical limitations.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] The AC power line frequency was used for the vertical refresh rate for two reasons.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] The first reason was that the television's vacuum tube was susceptible to interference from the unit's power supply, including residual ripple.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] This could cause drifting horizontal bars (hum bars).
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Using the same frequency reduced this, and made interference static on the screen and therefore less obtrusive.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] The second reason was that television studios would use AC lamps, filming at a different frequency would cause strobing.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Thus producers had little choice but to run sets at 60 Hz in America, and 50 Hz in Europe.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] These rates formed the basis for the sets used today: 60 Hz System M (almost always used with NTSC color coding) and 50 Hz System B/G (almost always used with PAL or SECAM color coding).
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] This accident of chance gave European sets higher resolution, in exchange for lower frame rates.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] However, the lower refresh rate of 50 Hz introduces more flicker, so sets that use digital technology to double the refresh rate to 100 Hz are now very popular.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Another difference between 50 Hz and 60 Hz standards is the way motion pictures (film sources as opposed to video camera sources) are transferred or presented.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] 35 mm film is typically shot at 24 frames per second (fps).
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] For PAL 50 Hz this allows film sources to be easily transferred by accelerating the film by 4%.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] The resulting picture is therefore smooth, however, there is a small shift in the pitch of the audio.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] NTSC sets display both 24 fps and 25 fps material without any speed shifting by using a technique called 3:2 pulldown, but at the expense of introducing unsmooth playback in the form of telecine judder.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Similar to some computer monitors and some DVDs, analog television systems use interlace, which decreases the apparent flicker by painting first the odd lines and then the even lines (these are known as fields).
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] This doubles the refresh rate, compared to a progressive scan image at the same frame rate.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] This works perfectly for video cameras, where each field results from a separate exposure – the effective frame rate doubles, there are now 50 rather than 25 exposures per second.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] The dynamics of a CRT are ideally suited to this approach, fast scenes will benefit from the 50 Hz refresh, the earlier field will have largely decayed away when the new field is written, and static images will benefit from improved resolution as both fields will be integrated by the eye.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Modern CRT-based televisions may be made flicker-free in the form of 100 Hz technology.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Many high-end LCD televisions now have a 120 or 240 Hz (current and former NTSC countries) or 100 or 200 Hz (PAL/SECAM countries) refresh rate.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] The rate of 120 was chosen as the least common multiple of 24 fps (cinema) and 30 fps (NTSC TV), and allows for less distortion when movies are viewed due to the elimination of telecine (3:2 pulldown).
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] For PAL at 25 fps, 100 or 200 Hz is used as a fractional compromise of the least common multiple of 600 (24 × 25).
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] These higher refresh rates are most effective from a 24p-source video output (e.g.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Blu-ray Disc), and/or scenes of fast motion.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] As movies are usually filmed at a rate of 24 frames per second, while television sets operate at different rates, some conversion is necessary.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Different techniques exist to give the viewer an optimal experience.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] The combination of content production, playback device, and display device processing may also give artifacts that are unnecessary.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] A display device producing a fixed 60 fps rate cannot display a 24 fps movie at an even, judder-free rate.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Usually a 3:2 pulldown is used, giving a slight uneven movement.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] In the case of material shot on video, improvements in smoothness just from having a higher refresh rate may be barely noticeable.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] In the case of filmed material, as 120 is an even multiple of 24, it is possible to present a 24 fps sequence without judder on a well-designed 120 Hz display (i.e., so-called 5-5 pulldown).
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] If the 120 Hz rate is produced by frame-doubling a 60 fps 3:2 pulldown signal, the uneven motion could still be visible (i.e., so-called 6-4 pulldown).
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] Additionally, material may be displayed with synthetically created smoothness with the addition of motion interpolation abilities to the display, which has an even larger effect on filmed material.
[src:game-loop-timing/refresh-rate] "50 Hz" TV sets (when fed with "50 Hz" content) usually get a movie that is slightly faster than normal, avoiding any problems with uneven pulldown.
